"Schneidereit A., Blender R., Fraedrich K.","A radius-depth model for midlatitude cyclones in reanalysis data and simulations",2010,"Quarterly Journal of the Royal Meteorological Society","136","646",,"50","60",,,10.1002/qj.523,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77249131208&partnerID=40&md5=acda413a769e781a441ae8837b3a2004","Meteorologisches Institut, Universität Hamburg, Klima Campus, Grindelberg 5, D-20144 Hamburg, Germany","Schneidereit, A., Meteorologisches Institut, Universität Hamburg, Klima Campus, Grindelberg 5, D-20144 Hamburg, Germany; Blender, R., Meteorologisches Institut, Universität Hamburg, Klima Campus, Grindelberg 5, D-20144 Hamburg, Germany; Fraedrich, K., Meteorologisches Institut, Universität Hamburg, Klima Campus, Grindelberg 5, D-20144 Hamburg, Germany","Geometric properties of winter (DJF) and summer (JJA) midlatitude cyclones are analysed in reanalysis data, present-day and global warming simulations. Cyclone centres are identified by the minima of the 1000hPa geopotential height. Fitting an azimuthally symmetric Gaussian function to the surrounding height field provides cyclonedepth(differencebetweenthecyclonecentreandthesynopticenvironment), radius (standard deviation), geostrophic wind and vorticity. Analysing ERA-40 reanalysis data of different resolutions and Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) scenario simulations by the coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation model ECHAM5/MPI-OM yields mean radii of 300-500km in winter and 300-400km in summer. Depth maxima occur in the storm tracks (determined by the bandpass-filtered variance of the geopotential height), and the smallest radii characterize oceanic cyclogenesis regions. The geostrophic vorticity, derived from thefittedGaussianmodel,agreesreasonablywellwiththeobservedrelativevorticity. Future warmer climate scenarios exhibit smaller radii and weaker depths during winter and summer. An intense growth of the depth is found during the 2-10 day cyclone life cycles, while the radii reveal negligible growth. Compositing depths with respect to normalized total lifetime leads to rescaled depth life cycles, which collapse to a simple universal function, ã(1 - ã), for relative cyclone age ã. © 2010 Royal Meteorological Society.","Climate change; Cyclone radius; Life cycles","Band pass; Climate scenarios; Compositing; Coupled atmosphere ocean general circulation model; Cyclogenesis; Cyclone radius; Depth models; Gaussian functions; Geometric properties; Geopotential height; Geostrophic vorticity; Geostrophic winds; Height fields; Intergovernmental panel on climate changes; Midlatitude cyclones; Reanalysis; Scenario simulations; Standard deviation; Storm track; Universal functions; Global warming; Oceanography; Storms; Vorticity; Climate models; atmosphere-ocean coupling; atmospheric dynamics; climate change; computer simulation; cyclogenesis; data assimilation; geopotential; life cycle analysis; numerical model; storm track; tropical cyclone; vorticity",,,,,,"Benestad, R.E., Chen, D., The use of a calculus-based cyclone identification method for generating storm statistics (2006) Tellus A, 58, pp. 473-486; Bengtsson, L., Hodges, K.I., Roeckner, E., Storm tracks and climate change (2006) J. Climate, 19, pp. 3518-3543; Blender, R., Fraedrich, K., Lunkeit, F., Identification of cyclone-track regimes in the North Atlantic (1997) Q. J. R. Meteorol. Soc, 123, pp. 727-741; Blender, R., Schubert, M., Cyclone tracking in different spatial and temporal resolutions (2000) Mon. Weather Rev, 128, pp. 377-384; Grigoriev, S., Gulev, S.K., Zolina, O., Innovative software facilities cyclone tracking and analysis. Eos, Trans (2000) Amer. Geophys. Union, 81, p. 170; Grotjahn, R., Castello, C., A study of frontal cyclone surface and 300-hPa geostrophic kinetic energy distribution and scale change (2000) Mon. Weather. Rev, 128, pp. 2865-2874; Grotjahn, R., Hodyss, D., Castello, C., Do frontal cyclones change size? Observed widths of North Pacif